40
00:01:40,028 --> 00:01:43,770
his algorithm for solving Simon's problem,

41
00:01:43,770 --> 00:01:45,930
which is another contrived problem

42
00:01:45,930 --> 00:01:47,970
that quantum computers can do faster

43
00:01:47,970 --> 00:01:49,800
than classical computers.

44
00:01:49,800 --> 00:01:51,903
But this one was really,

45
00:01:52,830 --> 00:01:55,380
I wanna say this was really
kind of like a blueprint

46
00:01:55,380 --> 00:01:57,471
for the factoring algorithm,

47
00:01:57,471 --> 00:02:02,370
then figured out how to
do Fourier transforms

48
00:02:02,370 --> 00:02:05,370
over Z mod P,

49
00:02:05,370 --> 00:02:08,490
where P's a smooth number
on a quantum computer.

50
00:02:08,490 --> 00:02:11,764
And then I think I got up
in the middle of the night

51
00:02:11,764 --> 00:02:14,217
and scribbled some stuff down,

52
00:02:14,217 --> 00:02:17,190
and that gave me a discreet log algorithm

53
00:02:17,190 --> 00:02:20,370
for primes that are one larger,

54
00:02:20,370 --> 00:02:22,830
where P minus one is smooth.

55
00:02:22,830 --> 00:02:24,060
And so a smooth number is one

56
00:02:24,060 --> 00:02:26,619
that has a lot of small factors.

57
00:02:26,619 --> 00:02:29,970
So I had a factoring
algorithm for smooth numbers.

58
00:02:29,970 --> 00:02:33,840
This algorithm was so different
from the classical algorithm

59
00:02:33,840 --> 00:02:36,450
that I think I, you know,

60
00:02:36,450 --> 00:02:38,970
it encouraged me rather
than discouraging me

61
00:02:38,970 --> 00:02:41,280
I played around with it quite a bit more,

62
00:02:41,280 --> 00:02:45,240
and I figured out how to use

63
00:02:45,240 --> 00:02:49,110
the Fourier transform
for P when P was smooth

64
00:02:49,110 --> 00:02:52,650
to factor to find the
discrete log for any number.

65
00:02:52,650 --> 00:02:54,000
I mean, that was great.

66
00:02:54,000 --> 00:02:55,530
That was, I could solve something

67
00:02:55,530 --> 00:02:57,090
with a quantum computer

68
00:02:57,090 --> 00:02:59,234
that you can't solve with
a classical computer.

69
00:02:59,234 --> 00:03:02,803
And it was, you know,

70
00:03:02,803 --> 00:03:04,110
a very important problem,

71
00:03:04,110 --> 00:03:08,610
because discreet logs are
used for crypto systems.

72
00:03:08,610 --> 00:03:12,240
I used to work on algorithm for
problems in computer science

73
00:03:12,240 --> 00:03:14,790
and now I work on quantum computing,

74
00:03:14,790 --> 00:03:17,010
so it's changed direction.

75
00:03:17,010 --> 00:03:18,210
I still kept working

76
00:03:18,210 --> 00:03:20,970
on traditional computer science algorithms

77
00:03:20,970 --> 00:03:22,590
for a few years after

78
00:03:22,590 --> 00:03:24,120
the factoring algorithm was discovered.

79
00:03:24,120 --> 00:03:26,640
But then I started doing more and more

80
00:03:26,640 --> 00:03:28,170
just quantum computing.

81
00:03:28,170 --> 00:03:31,710
And I guess the first thing
I did after quantum computing

82
00:03:31,710 --> 00:03:33,390
was quantum error correction.

83
00:03:33,390 --> 00:03:34,860
Without error correction,

84
00:03:34,860 --> 00:03:37,890
you can't get very far
on a quantum computer.

85
00:03:37,890 --> 00:03:40,470
My algorithm has completely
changed cryptography

86
00:03:40,470 --> 00:03:44,037
because cryptographers
now know that the RSA

87
00:03:44,037 --> 00:03:45,060
and Diffie-Hellman,

88
00:03:45,060 --> 00:03:46,620
and the old crypto systems

89
00:03:46,620 --> 00:03:49,410
is based on discrete log and factoring

90
00:03:49,410 --> 00:03:54,060
are not necessarily going
to be secure for ever.

91
00:03:54,060 --> 00:03:56,310
So they're trying to come up with

92
00:03:56,310 --> 00:03:58,920
quantum resistant crypto systems,

93
00:03:58,920 --> 00:04:02,730
and this has been an
immense area of research.

94
00:04:02,730 --> 00:04:04,740
We would really like to
make these crypto systems

95
00:04:04,740 --> 00:04:08,370
as efficient as possible without,

96
00:04:08,370 --> 00:04:11,070
you know, compromising them,

97
00:04:11,070 --> 00:04:14,550
and I really don't think
they know how to do that yet.

98
00:04:14,550 --> 00:04:17,430
So there's going to be a
lot more research on these.

