00:04:28,800 --> 00:04:32,550
I'm going to describe the steps
in the factoring algorithm.

105
00:04:32,550 --> 00:04:34,020
I'm not gonna explain why they work,

106
00:04:34,020 --> 00:04:36,420
because that would take
a really long time.

107
00:04:36,420 --> 00:04:39,780
But, so what do you do?

108
00:04:39,780 --> 00:04:44,700
Well, there's a part that
you do on a quantum computer,

109
00:04:44,700 --> 00:04:46,560
and then there's post-processing

110
00:04:46,560 --> 00:04:48,810
that you do on a classical computer.

111
00:04:48,810 --> 00:04:50,250
And the factoring algorithm,

112
00:04:50,250 --> 00:04:54,220
you want to find

113
00:04:55,230 --> 00:04:58,050
P x Q = N.

114
00:04:58,050 --> 00:04:59,670
So you're given N,

115
00:04:59,670 --> 00:05:02,130
and you wanna find two primes

116
00:05:02,130 --> 00:05:03,543
that multiply to N.

117
00:05:04,470 --> 00:05:09,310
And start with

118
00:05:10,620 --> 00:05:11,973
two quantum registers.

119
00:05:13,356 --> 00:05:17,148
(chalk scratching on board)

120
00:05:17,148 --> 00:05:19,440
And these are just basically registers

121
00:05:19,440 --> 00:05:21,270
that are supervision of numbers.

122
00:05:21,270 --> 00:05:22,323
The first one,

123
00:05:24,570 --> 00:05:27,850
so the first one has 2L qubits

124
00:05:30,150 --> 00:05:32,013
and the second one has L qubits.

125
00:05:33,450 --> 00:05:35,850
And you start the first register,

126
00:05:35,850 --> 00:05:37,800
well you start them all

127
00:05:37,800 --> 00:05:42,800
in say zero.

128
00:05:46,260 --> 00:05:48,870
So every qubit is in the state zero.

129
00:05:48,870 --> 00:05:52,260
And now what you do is
you apply a transformation

130
00:05:52,260 --> 00:05:56,973
that takes this state to
one over two zero plus one,

131
00:05:59,400 --> 00:06:00,233
to the 2L.

132
00:06:01,680 --> 00:06:04,510
And now this is the same as

133
00:06:05,760 --> 00:06:10,350
summation over I = 10 through two

134
00:06:10,350 --> 00:06:12,153
to the 2L - 1.

135
00:06:14,100 --> 00:06:15,210
I'm sorry,

136
00:06:15,210 --> 00:06:19,000
I with one over two to the L

137
00:06:19,890 --> 00:06:22,143
normalization factor
in front of it is zero.

138
00:06:24,570 --> 00:06:26,490
Now the next thing you do

139
00:06:26,490 --> 00:06:29,370
is you choose a random number X.

140
00:06:29,370 --> 00:06:33,477
Well, I choose random X

141
00:06:37,110 --> 00:06:39,513
with zero less than X, less than N.

142
00:06:42,090 --> 00:06:44,230
And now you compute

143
00:06:47,730 --> 00:06:49,030
X to the I

144
00:06:50,070 --> 00:06:53,193
mod N in the second register.

145
00:06:54,384 --> 00:06:59,384
(gentle music)
(chalk scratching on board)

146
00:07:00,960 --> 00:07:02,280
And now what you do is you take

147
00:07:02,280 --> 00:07:04,510
the quantum Fourier transform

148
00:07:05,730 --> 00:07:07,972
of the first register,

149
00:07:07,972 --> 00:07:10,555
(gentle music)

150
00:07:16,380 --> 00:07:21,380
and you measure the first register,

151
00:07:24,150 --> 00:07:26,793
and this will give you,

152
00:07:27,720 --> 00:07:29,640
well this will give you a number,

153
00:07:29,640 --> 00:07:32,370
but the wonderful link of the number

154
00:07:32,370 --> 00:07:34,500
is that you can then take this number,

155
00:07:34,500 --> 00:07:37,140
and do some post-processing on it.

156
00:07:37,140 --> 00:07:39,450
So basically you do

157
00:07:39,450 --> 00:07:42,420
continued fraction algorithm,

158
00:07:42,420 --> 00:07:44,771
and it will give you

159
00:07:44,771 --> 00:07:47,493
the factors of N if you're lucky.

